     2→//! src/module_50.rs
     3→//!
     4→//! Ledger Entry Query Service with pagination, request-level validation and
     5→//! Redis-backed response caching.  This module deliberately focuses on the
     6→//! “Query” half of CQRS, while remaining agnostic of the web framework that
     7→//! ultimately wires it up to REST/GraphQL routes.
     8→//!
     9→//! The code is intended to be production–ready: it embraces asynchronous I/O,
    10→//! proper error handling, structured logging (via `tracing`) and defensive
    11→//! validation.  It also demonstrates the Repository pattern, exposing a domain
    12→//! interface and hiding persistence details (PostgreSQL in our case).
    13→//!
    14→//! NOTE: Some crate features (e.g. `sqlx` macros) require the corresponding
    15→//! Cargo.toml declarations elsewhere in the project:
    16→//
    17→//! ```toml
    18→//! [dependencies]
    19→//! async-trait = "0.1"
    20→//! chrono       = { version = "0.4", features = ["serde"] }
    21→//! deadpool-redis = { version = "0.13", features = ["tokio1"] }
    22→//! redis        = { version = "0.23", default-features = false, features = ["aio"] }
    23→//! serde        = { version = "1", features = ["derive"] }
    24→//! sqlx         = { version = "0.7", features = ["runtime-tokio-rustls", "postgres", "chrono"] }
    25→//! thiserror    = "1"
    26→//! tracing      = "0.1"
    27→//! uuid         = { version = "1", features = ["serde", "v4"] }
    28→//! ```
    29→//!
    30→//! # Overview
    31→//!
    32→//! • `LedgerEntry`: Domain Model  
    33→//! • `LedgerEntryView`: DTO for external representation  
    34→//! • `Pagination`: Helper for page/size bounds + validation  
    35→//! • `LedgerEntryRepository`: Trait exposing database access  
    36→//! • `PostgresLedgerEntryRepository`: SQLx implementation  
    37→//! • `LedgerQueryService`: Orchestrates repository and cache
    38→
    39→#![allow(clippy::missing_errors_doc)] // Errors are documented in `LedgerError`
